# Sharing {{PROJECT_NAME}} with OpenSharing

This project can be shared **zero-copy** with [OpenSharing](https://github.com/OpenSharing-IO/OpenSharing) â€” "the open
sharing protocol for the agentic era" (Linux Foundation, Apache 2.0, [Delta Sharing](https://delta.io/sharing/)-compatible).
The data and AI assets stay in your own object storage; a recipient discovers what's shared and is handed **short-lived,
scoped credentials** to read each asset directly. Nothing is moved or duplicated. `share.json` beside this file declares what
is shared; `share-profile.example.json` is the recipient-side profile.

## What this project shares

OpenSharing organizes assets as **Share â†’ Schema â†’ Asset**. This project's share (`{{PROJECT_SLUG}}`, schema `processed`):

| From the project | Shared as | Where it lives |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `data/processed/` (as Delta / Iceberg / Parquet) | **Table** | `{{SHARE_STORAGE_BASE}}/data/processed/â€¦` |
| `documentation/`, `knowledge/`, file directories | **Volume** | `{{SHARE_STORAGE_BASE}}/documentation/â€¦` |
| `.skills/<name>` (AgentSkills) | **AgentSkill** | `{{SHARE_STORAGE_BASE}}/.skills/â€¦` |

Edit `share.json` to list your real processed tables and skill directories (the names must match the directories in storage),
to add or remove schemas, and to set `format`/`accessModes` per table.

## Serve it (provider)

1. **Put the assets in object storage.** Land `data/processed` as Delta/Iceberg/Parquet and your files/skills under `{{SHARE_STORAGE_BASE}}` (S3, GCS, Azure Blob, or Cloudflare R2).
2. **Run a sharing server.** Stand up an OpenSharing / Delta-Sharing-compatible server and configure its shares, schemas, and assets from `share.json` (map each object's `location`/`storageLocation` to the storage paths above).
3. **The server vends access.** On request it returns temporary, scoped credentials (`awsTempCredentials` / `azureUserDelegationSas` / `gcpOauthToken` / `r2Credentials`) with an `expirationTime` â€” least privilege, per asset, time-boxed. You revoke access by rotating the recipient's bearer token or removing the asset; because sharing is in place, you always control the source.

## Consume it (recipient)

1. Copy the example profile and fill in the token your provider vended â€” **this file holds a secret, so keep it out of git**:

   ```bash
   cp share-profile.example.json share-profile.json   # then paste the bearerToken; share-profile.json is gitignored
   ```

2. Read the share with any Delta Sharing client (`pip install delta-sharing`; Spark, DuckDB, Power BI, Tableau, Snowflake also work):

   ```python
   import delta_sharing
   client = delta_sharing.SharingClient("share-profile.json")
   print(client.list_shares())                 # discover what you can read
   df = delta_sharing.load_as_pandas("share-profile.json#{{PROJECT_SLUG}}.processed.{{PROJECT_SLUG}}")
   ```

The profile points at `{{OPENSHARING_ENDPOINT}}`; add `"icebergEndpoint"` if you serve Iceberg tables.

## How this fits the other L5 surfaces

OpenSharing shares the **live data and AI assets** (zero-copy, governed). It complements the project's other publish surfaces:
the **OKF** `knowledge/` bundle shares the *understanding*, the **ARD** `ai-catalog.json` *advertises* that these resources exist
(the AgentSkill here is the same `.skills/` it lists), and the **Dataverse** deposit archives a *frozen, citable copy* with a DOI.
Use OpenSharing when partners need working access without taking a copy; use the deposit when you need a permanent citation.

<!-- IF:SENSITIVE -->## Sensitive data â€” govern what enters the share

This project handles **{{SENSITIVITY_TIER}}** data. Scoped, expiring credentials are a **control, not a license** to share what
shouldn't be shared. Decide what enters the share with the access tiers in `GOVERNANCE.md`, and complete the
`responsible-data-checklist` first: desensitize before an asset becomes shareable, scope the recipient to the minimum assets,
or withhold identifiable/restricted assets entirely. Never place identifiable, regulated, or Indigenous-data (CARE) assets in an
open share. Because access is continuous, treat token rotation and revocation as part of the governance, not an afterthought.<!-- /IF -->
